# **Game Design Document: Backside of the Moon**

## **Game Summary**

"Backside of the Moon" is a 3D first-person roguelike horror game that immerses players in a twisted world. The protagonist travels through a series of rooms via an elevator. In these rooms, you may hide & run from unpredictable monsters, solve puzzles & escape from rooms, make difficult choices, and finally piece together clues to unravel truths of the world. 

## **Genre**

Rogue-like, horror, mockumentary, single-player. 

## **Inspiration**

[**Backrooms.**](https://store.steampowered.com/app/1987080/Inside\_the\_Backrooms/)
![backrooms](images/backrooms.png)

We are all impressed by the simplistic art style of Backroom’s room designs, which creates a sense of isolation and horror, even in the provided vast spaces. We want to create rooms that have similar art styles, where the familiar becomes unsettlingly unfamiliar.

[**Inscryption.**](https://store.steampowered.com/app/1092790/Inscryption/)
![Inscryption](images/incryption.png)
Inspired by the boss designs in Inscryption, where creatures are defined by their vague shapes and key features like floating eyes and hands, we aim to create monsters that would evoke a similar sense of psychological horror. 

[**Classrooms.**](https://store.steampowered.com/app/2099110/The\_Classrooms/)
![classrooms](images/classrooms.png)
Our user interface style choice (mockumentary) is inspired from this game to promote a realistic sense. The health is represented as the battery of the camera. The monsters can either be sensitive to movement, light, or sound, which makes those the key elements to escape from specific rooms.

[**Fork Road.**](https://store.steampowered.com/app/2976400/Fork\_Road/) 
![forkroad](images/forkroad.png)
This game inspires the design of our Choice rooms. We want to incorporate several psychological tricks, such as distraction, to make the choice process more interesting and horrifying. 

[**SCP.**](https://scp-wiki.wikidot.com/)
![scp](images/scp.png)
SCP (Secure,Contain, Protect) Foundation inspires our story set ups: this universe has many anomalies, which can be either creatures or objects with supernatural power. The anomalies are “contained” by the SCP Foundation to protect humanity. 

## **Platform**

The game is developed to be released on Mac and Windows PC.

## **Development Software**

JMonkey Engine

## **Gameplay**

Main mechanism: 

We have 3 types of rooms: Monster rooms (run, hide, or fight), Choice rooms (turning right or left to make a choice, and a different choice would trigger different effects), and Escape rooms (players interact with objects in the room, and solve the puzzle to get the key out). 

For each type of the room, there will be a hidden item, which provides help when the player enters into the next room with the same type. Rooms are categorized into three distinct levels: Level 1, Level 2, and Level 3\. While the appearance of rooms within each level is randomized (thus creating a dynamic rogue-like experience), lower-level rooms will always appear before higher-level rooms. This ensures that players encounter and interact with items from lower levels before progressing to those from higher levels.

After all items are collected, the true ending will be released (otherwise the player can only reach a fake ending). After clearing the true ending, the player will get a pistol with infinite ammos in the second round of the game, which can beat the monsters and break the locks in the puzzle rooms directly. 

Story: 

The fake ending is the player finding out he or she is isolated on the moon. The true ending is the same setting (on the moon), but with a mirror for him to realize that he is not a human but only a pair of hands floating in the air. He is one of the contained abnormalities. By knowing this, he becomes immortal and thus able to fight all the monsters if the player restarts the game.

We also decide to design a plentiful of side stories for the rooms, leaving clues such as the items from the last character who wanted to escape. The interaction between the monster is another aspect we want to spend time with, for example, if in the previous room the player decides to help rather than fight a certain abnormality, then this monster will jump out and help the player to fight against another monster. We want to incorporate clues about the relationship between the monsters with minimum words but mostly by visual expression.

## **Visual Design**

User Interface:

As for the mockumentary style, we would not incorporate too many elements on the canvas, but simply health (shown as the battery of the camera), backpack, and save/load button. 

Text Information: 

We want to minimize the direct expression by text, especially to avoid a whole big paragraph of words. Instead, we propose to use the fragmental texts, such as a few bloody red words appearing on the arms of our main character, to provide the information. 

Scene transition: 

One special design of our game is that everytime the player has passed or cleared a room, the player will not directly go into the next room but into a transition zone \- an elevator. It will be a softer way for us to load the new map (room), and a more stylistic way to show the information, such as the progress of item collection and room discovery, by writing those on the wall of the elevator. The elevator will also provide the entrance for the true ending with a full item collection with a suddenly appeared door on the other side.
